tool.name: Centerline

param.name: WorkspaceLocation
param.dialogReference:
First we need to set our workspace. This allows the tool to know where to save your GGLREM.csv table. Each GGLREM project should be self containted in a unique folder.

Remember, ArcMap will only include "connected folders" in the file explorer. So, if you are working off a USB drive, or have you DEM stored in a new location, you may need to use "Connect To Folder" to make the location available.

param.name: geoLocation
param.dialogReference:
Next, we set our project geodatabase (.gdb). You will need to create a New File Geodatabase (upper righthand corner) if one does not already exist.

In most cases the user will be creating the unique project geodatabase in this step. You do not need a new geodatabase for each Centerline Feature Class.
param.pythonReference: Creates a variable that references the location of the project geodatabase.

param.name: CoordinateSystem
param.displayname: Match Coordinate System to LiDAR DEM
param.dialogReference:
Match the coordinate system of your LiDAR data with your output Feature Classes.

If you already have your DEM loaded on your map you can look in the "Layers" folder to select the CRC. Otherwise you can click the dropdown arrow next to the globe icon and select "Import." Then, simply navigate to, and select your DEM.
param.pythonReference: Creates a variable that references the Coordinate Reference System (CRS) of the input DEM.

param.name: CenterlineName
param.dialogReference:
Finally, we input a uniquename for the centerline feature class. Remember, that additional centerlines may be drawn, so it is a good idea to add your intials or some other additional unique id to the name.

This Polyline Feature Class will be used to draw the Geomorphic Grade Line.
param.pythonReference: Creates a Polyline Feature Class with a required column named "RouteID."

tool.summary:
This first tool is a maintentance step with the goal to reduce potentnial errors for users new to ArcMap.

  1. First we need to set our workspace. This allows the tool to know where to save your GGLREM.csv table. Each GGLREM project should be self containted in a unique folder.

  2. Next, we set our project geodatabase (.gdb). You will need to create a New File Geodatabase (upper righthand corner) if one does not already exist.

  3. Then, we reference the coordinate system of your Digital Elevation Model to make sure the features we create will match.

  4. Finally, we input a uniquename for the centerline feature class. Remember, that additional centerlines may be drawn, so it is a good idea to add your intials or some other additional unique id to the name.

IMPORTANT!!! This tool assumes, and requires, that your DEM is projected onto a 1m square grid like UTM. While the earth is most certianly round, our map is definately flat!

Make sure you have the latest and greatest GGLREM Toolbox: https://github.com/helstab/GGLREM
